Values, types, and the type system.

Every value in Java has a type that the compiler knows at compile time, and those types come in two flavours. Primitive types are built into the language and store their value directly: things like int, long, double, boolean, and char. Reference types are everything else. Every class is a reference type, and a reference-typed variable holds a reference, essentially a pointer, to an object that lives on the heap. A string, a list, an array, and any class you define are all reference types.

This distinction matters because of where the data lives. A primitive sits right on the stack with its value embedded. A reference value is a pointer on the stack that leads to an object allocated on the heap. We come back to this picture in module seven, when we look at java virtual machine memory.

There is one more wrinkle. Every primitive has a boxed partner that is a reference type: int pairs with Integer, boolean pairs with Boolean, and so on. The compiler automatically boxes and unboxes between them whenever it needs to. That is convenient, but boxing allocates a real object, so inside a hot loop you prefer the plain primitive.
